1 Month</div></div><div
class="how-to-desc"><div
class="how-to-image">
<picture>
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-how-to-incorporate-completed-800x800-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=250&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="250" height="250" alt="How to Incorporate:">
</picture></div><p>Follow our step-by-step guide if you would like to incorporate your business.</p></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section1" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>1.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=decide-if-incorporating-is-the-right-choice>Decide if incorporating is the right choice.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section1-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>1.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=evaluate-the-pros-and-cons-of-incorporating>Evaluate the pros and cons of incorporating.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-consider-the-pros-and-cons-of-incorporating-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Evaluate the pros and cons of incorporating."></div></div><p>The first step is to carefully consider the benefits and drawbacks of incorporating and to evaluate whether this is the right move for your business.</p><p><strong>Advantages include:</strong></p><ul><li>Personal asset protection.</li><li>Adds business credibility.</li><li>Affords name protection.</li><li>Perpetual existence.</li><li>Easier to raise capital.</li><li>Easy to transfer ownership.</li></ul><p><strong>Disadvantages include:</strong></p><ul><li>Double taxation.</li><li>Time-consuming formalities.</li><li>Regular filings and annual fees.</li><li>Additional paperwork.</li><li>Shared ownership.</li><li>More difficult to dissolve.</li></ul></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section1-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>1.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=seek-professional-advice>Seek professional advice.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-seek-professional-advice-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Seek professional advice."></div></div><p>Consult with your accountant and lawyer to gain a better understanding of the financial and legal implications of incorporating.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section2" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>2.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=decide-which-state-to-incorporate-in>Decide which state(s) to incorporate in.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section2-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>2.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=incorporate-in-the-state-where-your-business-is-located>Incorporate in the state where your business is located.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-consider-incorporating-in-the-state-of-your-primary-business-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Incorporate in the state where your business is located."></div></div><p>Deciding to incorporate in the state of your primary business is the least complicated option. Incorporating in your home state is sensible for businesses only operating in that state since, regardless of the state of incorporation, the business must still be registered and pay fees and taxes in every state in which it operates.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section2-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>2.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=research-your-options-for-incorporating-out-of-state>Research your options for incorporating out-of-state.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-research-your-options-for-incorporating-out-of-state-288x288-20200824.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Research your options for incorporating out-of-state."></div></div><p>Incorporating out-of-state may be financially advantageous. If you have or intend to have active business locations in several states, it is worth researching the tax regulations, costs of incorporation, and out-of-state qualifications in <a
href="#guides-to-starting-a-business-by-state">each state</a> to determine whether it might be more cost-efficient to incorporate out-of-state.</p><div
class="step-direction tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>Some states, like <a
href="https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-start-a-business-in-georgia">Georgia</a> and <a
href="https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-start-a-business-in-utah">Utah</a>, are more business-friendly than others, making them a popular choice for larger companies.</p></div></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section3" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>3.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=find-a-business-name>Find a business name.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section3-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=research-the-rules-for-business-names-in-your-state>Research the rules for business names in your state.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-research-the-rules-for-business-names-in-your-state-288x288-20200827.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Research the rules for business names in your state."></div></div><p>To ensure compliance you should familiarize yourself with the <a
href="#guides-to-starting-a-business-by-state">state's</a> naming rules. Keep in mind that usually the name must be unique and end with a designator such as Inc., Co., or Corp.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section3-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=create-a-list-of-potential-names>Create a list of potential names.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-create-a-list-of-potential-business-names-288x288-20200827_2020-08-27-070510.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Create a list of potential names."></div></div><p>Take keywords from your market research and brainstorm name ideas.</p><div
class="step-direction tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>Use a <a
href="https://www.namesnack.com/">business name generator</a> to create name ideas.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section3-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=ask-potential-clients-for-their-opinion>Ask potential clients for their opinion.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-ask-potential-clients-for-their-opinion-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Ask potential clients for their opinion."></div></div><p>Find out what your target market thinks of your business name ideas by posting online surveys or approaching them in person.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section3-step4" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.4&nbsp;</span><h4 id=trademark-your-business-name>Trademark your business name.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-trademark-your-business-name-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Trademark your business name."></div></div><p>Once you have decided on a name, you should trademark it to ensure that no other business uses it. You can search the <a
href="https://www.uspto.gov/trademarks/search">USPTO trademark database</a> to see if your name idea is available.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section4" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>4.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=form-your-business>Form your business.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section4-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>4.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=decide-on-the-type-of-corporation>Decide on the type of corporation.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-decide-on-the-type-of-corporation-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Decide on the type of corporation."></div></div><p>The two main types of corporations are C and S corporations. The main differences between the two are how they are taxed, the number of shareholders they can have, and how much stock can be issued.</p><p><strong>A C corporation is good for fast-growing businesses that eventually want to go public.</strong> This type of corporation is subject to corporate taxes but is not limited in the number of shareholders and class of stock that can be issued.</p><p><strong>An S corporation is essentially a C corporation that qualifies for pass-through taxation.</strong> After incorporating, a business is automatically a C corporation. To become an S corporation, the business must apply for S corporation status. The requirements to qualify as an S corporation include the following:</p><ul><li>The business must be based in the U.S. and filed as a U.S. corporation.</li><li>The number of shareholders is limited to 100.</li><li>Shareholders must be U.S. citizens or residents.</li><li>Only one class of stock can be issued.</li></ul><div
class="step-direction tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>File Form 2553 with the IRS should you want to apply for S corporation status.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section4-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>4.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=appoint-a-registered-agent>Appoint a registered agent.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-appoint-a-registered-agent-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Appoint a registered agent."></div></div><p>Most U.S. states require businesses to appoint a registered agent. A registered agent is a corporation's official contact for communicating with the state. Corporations can appoint an individual or another company to act as their registered agent.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section4-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>4.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=prepare-and-file-articles-of-incorporation>Prepare and file articles of incorporation.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-prepare-and-file-for-articles-of-incorporation-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Prepare and file articles of incorporation."></div></div><p>The articles of incorporation refer to the legal document businesses are required to complete and file with their secretary of state office to create a corporation. Filing fees vary by <a
href="#guides-to-starting-a-business-by-state">state</a>.</p><p>Articles of incorporation typically include the following:</p><ul><li>Name of the corporation.</li><li>Purpose of the corporation.</li><li>Name and address of the appointed registered agent.</li><li>Type of corporation.</li><li>Duration of the corporation.</li><li>Names and addresses of the initial board of directors.</li><li>Name and signature of the incorporator.</li></ul></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section5" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>5.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=create-corporate-bylaws>Create corporate bylaws.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section5-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=draw-up-a-set-of-bylaws>Draw up a set of bylaws.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-draw-up-a-set-of-bylaws-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Draw up a set of bylaws."></div></div><p>Corporate bylaws are the rules that outline how business operations are to be run and what procedures must be followed. It usually contains provisions regarding the way the corporation is to conduct business and defines the powers, duties, and responsibilities of the board of directors, officers, and employees.</p><p>Corporations are required to draw up a set of bylaws to guide operations and ensure that all business activities and decisions are recorded for future reference.</p><p><strong>Corporate bylaws are the rules of a corporation and generally include the following:</strong></p><ul><li>The corporation's identifying information.</li><li>Stock classes and type of shares the corporation issues.</li><li>The composition, powers, and duties of the board of directors, corporate officers, and committees.</li><li>Procedures and intervals for holding various types of meetings.</li><li>Shareholder voting rights.</li><li>Procedure for making amendments to the corporation's bylaws and Articles of Incorporation.</li><li>Corporate record-keeping procedures.</li><li>A Conflict of Interest Policy.</li></ul></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section5-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=start-a-corporate-records-book>Start a corporate records book.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-start-a-corporate-records-book-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Start a corporate records book."></div></div><p>Corporations are required to maintain a corporate records book. This is where the corporation's essential documents and records that track operations and major decisions are kept.</p><p><strong>A corporate records book contains an organization's essential documents and records such as:</strong></p><ul><li>Articles of Corporation.</li><li>Corporate bylaws.</li><li>Meeting minutes.</li><li>Stock certificates.</li></ul></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section5-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=hold-the-first-board-meeting>Hold the first board meeting.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-hold-the-first-board-meeting-288x288-20200821.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Hold the first board meeting."></div></div><p>The incorporator is responsible for organizing the very first board meeting of a new corporation in which the initial board of directors officially adopts the corporate bylaws, elects a permanent board of directors, issues stocks, and makes other pertinent resolutions.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section6" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>6.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=apply-for-necessary-permits-and-licenses>Apply for necessary permits and licenses.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section6-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=check-your-state-requirements>Check your state requirements.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-check-your-state-requirements-288x288-20200825.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Check your state requirements."></div></div><p>Navigate to your secretary of state website to find out if there are <a
href="#guides-to-starting-a-business-by-state">state-specific</a> permits and licenses that you need to apply for.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section6-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=get-an-employer-identification-number>Get an Employer Identification Number (EIN).</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/irs-ein-application-288x288-20200624.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Get an Employer Identification Number (EIN)."></div></div><p>Businesses need an <a
href="https://www.zarla.com/guides/how-to-apply-for-an-ein">EIN</a> for tax purposes if they plan to hire employees.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-incorporate-section6-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=file-a-doing-business-as>File a Doing Business As (DBA).</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
